text.tspan: Data Rate and Clocking in OOK
Relation between Gbps, GHz, and Rise Time
The illustration below shows two pulses (high and low), with following parameters:
Tfund: Period of the fundamental frequency. This is in the case when data continuously
oscillate between high and low, essentially behaving like a rectangular signal.
Trise: Rise time -- transition between high and low (assuming fall time being the same).
Tpeak: Time duration in which a pulse holds its level.

tspan.tspan: In the plots below I depicted data using sinusoidal, which represent the minimum
required bandwidth to achieve certain data rate while avoiding ISI effects (Nyquist limit).

text.tspan: From the plot we can read the following:
In the case of OOK systems, there are two ways the data can be clocked/sampled:
Double data rate (DDR) clocking: in one clock cycle two data pulses get clocked.
Single data rate (SDR) clocking: in one clock cycle one data pulse gets clocked.
